{"id":14880756,"mediaExerciseId":"00a1fd39-61d9-4617-ac73-830cd1818d7d","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612265,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":43,"solutions":[{"id":5900712,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are asked to determine the operating cash flow of Pompeii, Inc..","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/88c92fd2df8c2cd705012d74bc75b801/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/88c92fd2df8c2cd705012d74bc75b801/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first define operating cash flow. \n\n- **Operating Cash Flow** measures the amount of cash generated by a company's normal business operation.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/687bb377d110f791ce48cd3a72a6d7a7/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/687bb377d110f791ce48cd3a72a6d7a7/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Operating Cash Flow is computed as follows:\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Operating Cash Flow} &= \\text{EBIT} + {\\text{Depreciation}} -  {\\text{Taxes}}\\\\[1pt]\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nWhere:\n\nEBIT - Earnings Before Interests and Taxes\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":197,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/1f5367b235a9c37dcc64edc647bef821/lateximg_large.png","width":856},"regular":{"height":100,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/1f5367b235a9c37dcc64edc647bef821/lateximg.png","width":429}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's identify the given amounts in the problem.\n\n|Particulars | Amounts ($) | \n|--|--:| \n|Sales | 46,200| \n|Costs | 23,100| \n| Depreciation Expense|2,200 | \n| Interest Expense | 1,700|\n\nThe tax expense is 22%.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we compute for the operating cash flow, we will first calculate the EBIT as shown below:\n\n$$\\begin {array}{lrr}\n\\text{Sales}&\\$\\hspace{5pt}\\text{46,200}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Cost of Goods Sold}&\\underline{\\text{23,100}}\\\\\n\\text{Gros Profit}&\\text{\\$\\hspace{5pt}23,100}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Depreciation expense}&\\underline{\\text{2,200}}\\\\\n\\textbf{Earnings Before Interest and Taxes}&\\underline{\\underline{\\$\\hspace{5pt}\\textbf{20,900}}}\\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":295,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/6b1d52a9dabb9627d71cfcd2b1282925/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":148,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/6b1d52a9dabb9627d71cfcd2b1282925/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Then, we will compute for the taxes.\n\n$$\\begin {array}{lrr}\n\\text{Earnings Before Interest and Taxes}&\\$\\hspace{5pt}\\text{20,900}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Interest Expense}&\\underline{\\text{1,700}}\\\\\n\\text{Taxable Income}&\\text{\\$\\hspace{5pt}19,200}\\\\\n\\text{Tax Rate}&\\underline{\\text{\\hspace{10pt}22\\%}}\\\\\n\\textbf{Income Tax Expense }&\\underline{\\underline{\\$\\hspace{5pt}\\textbf{4,224}}}\\\\\n\\end{array}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":257,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/5c6d511f1058a259bd426027df927b91/lateximg_large.png","width":803},"regular":{"height":129,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/e50785b9301f78d8fc34d02dbfd9cd9b/5c6d511f1058a259bd426027df927b91/lateximg.png","width":402}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Now that we have computed the EBIT and taxes, let's now compute for the operating cash flow using the equation in step 3.\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Operating Cash Flow} &= \\text{EBIT} + {\\text{Depreciation}} -  {\\text{Taxes}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\text{\\$20,900} + {\\text{2,200}} -  {\\text{4,224}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\boxed{\\textbf{\\$18,876}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nTherefore, the operating cash flow of Pompeii, Inc. is **$18,876**.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"e906fde7-e46a-49df-bd56-15f26b88ef39","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":7}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880757,"exerci